l freeze on the building, testing, and deployment of nuclear weapons on the part of two superpowers of the US and the USSR. That simple but powerful proposition stirred popular sentiment and provoked protest in the streets and on screen from New York City to London to Berlin. Movie stars and scholars, bishops and reverends, governors and congress members, and, ultimately, US President Reagan and General Secretary Gorbachev took a stand for or against the Freeze proposal. With the Reagan administration so openly discussing the prospect of winnable and survivable nuclear warfare like never before, the Freeze movement forcefully translated decades of private fears into public action. Drawing upon extensive archival research in recently declassified materials, Maar illuminates how the Freeze campaign demonstrated the power and importance of grassroots peace activism in all levels of society. The Freeze movement played an instrumental role in shaping public opinion and American politics, helping establish the conditions that would bring the Cold War to an end.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAntinuclear movementzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCold War. 0aNuclear arms controlzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNuclear weaponsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 4aCold War History. 4aDiplomatic History. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aNuclear Weapons Freeze Campaign, 1980s antinuclear activism, International Campaign for the Abolition of Nuclear Weapons, INF Treaty, 1980s anti-Reagan films and music, National Committee for a Sane Nuclear Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978